@article{Taylor2010,
abstract = {Objective: Daily adult human exposure to bisphenol A (BPA) has been estimated at less than one µg/kg with virtually complete first pass conjugation in the liver in primates but not mice. We measured serum unconjugated and conjugated BPA levels in adult female rhesus monkeys and mice following oral administration of BPA, and compared findings in mice and monkeys with prior published data in women. Methods: Eleven adult female rhesus macaques were fed 400 µg/kg deuterated BPA daily for seven days. Levels of serum dBPA were analyzed by isotope dilution LC-MS (0.2 ng/ml limit of detection) over 24 h on day 1 and 7. The same dose of BPA was fed to adult female CD-1 mice; other female mice were administered 3H-BPA from 2 to 100,000 µg/kg. Results: In monkeys the maximum serum unconjugated dBPA concentration of 4 ng/ml was reached at 1 h after feeding and declined to low levels by 24 h, with no significant bioaccumulation after 7 daily doses. Adult female mice and rhesus monkeys cleared serum unconjugated BPA at virtually identical rates. There was a linear relationship between administered dose and serum BPA in mice. Conclusions: BPA pharmacokinetics in women, female monkeys and mice is very similar. By comparison with \~{}2 ng/ml serum unconjugated BPA reported in multiple human studies, the average 24 h serum unconjugated BPA concentration of 0.5 ng/ml in both monkeys and mice following a 400-µg/kg oral dose suggests that total daily human exposure is via multiple routes and much higher than previously assumed.},
